ively higher from 14 July onwards, printing a sequence of higher closes that has carried it more than 250 pips to current levels. The acceleration through mid-July was particularly notable, with the 14 July session punching through the upper boundary of that prior consolidation and triggering follow-through across the subsequent sessions. Since 21 July, price has been digesting those gains in a tight, orderly fashion \u2014 three consecutive daily candles with relatively modest ranges and closes clustered around 114.18\u2013114.25. That kind of measured consolidation after a strong impulse leg is typically consistent with a trend that is pausing rather than reversing.\n\nFrom a zone perspective, the prior reaction zone at 114.33 has capped three intraday attempts over the past two sessions, making it the immediate overhead reference. Below current price, the prior reaction zone at 113.95 \u2014 which attracted four touches during the mid-July advance \u2014 represents the first meaningful structural support. Should that give way, the 113.21 zone comes into view, an area that provided a platform for the breakout push earlier this month.\n\nThe H1 picture reflects the same consolidation theme seen on the daily. Since the early hours of 23 July, price has been drifting gradually lower from the 114.48 session high, finding a floor around 114.09 during the Asian session this morning before recovering to the 114.25 area through the London open. The hourly structure shows a series of lower highs from the 114.48 peak, but crucially, each dip has been contained \u2014 there is no impulsive selling pressure evident, more a gentle drift that is consistent with position digestion ahead of the next directional move. The 10:00 candle's push back to 114.32 before fading suggests the prior reaction zone overhead remains the key near-term battleground.\n\nToday's economic calendar carries no scheduled high-impact events for either the Australian dollar or the Japanese yen, which means price action is likely to be driven by broader risk sentiment and any residual positioning flows rather than data-driven volatility. A quiet calendar can sometimes allow technically-driven moves to develop more cleanly, though it also means liquidity can be thinner and ranges compressed.\n\nWhat would alter the bullish read? A daily close back beneath the 113.95 prior reaction zone would suggest the consolidation has morphed into something more corrective, and a move through 113.21 would materially undermine the short-term trend structure. On the upside, a sustained break and hold above 114.33 would open the path toward the 114.48 recent high and beyond.\n\nThis is editorial analysis, not financial advice. Trading involves substantial risk of loss.", "sample": false}